<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="18" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,760,1725,2068]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,286,1725,1748]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Description.</emphasis>
Length 2.0 mm (measured along the ventral side), maximum width 
<quantity box="[392,475,1757,1780]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" unit="mm" value="1.4">1.4 mm</quantity>
. General shape roughly hemispherical, with posterior half slightly elongated (
<figureCitation box="[659,746,1789,1812]" captionStart="Figs 2–7" captionStartId="2.[151,188,1643,1662]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,189,1627]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,189,1630]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 2–7.Amber inclusion of Platypelochares electricus sp. nov. 2 – amber piece with the studied specimen.3–7 – morphological details of P.electricus: 3 – ventral view; 4 – detail of the tubercle row on the pronotum (indicated by an arrow); 5 – detail of the ventral side of prosternum and right hypomeron, with the excavation (indicated by an arrow); 6 – lateral view; 7 – metacoxa and first four abdominal ventrites (arrow – lateral articulation of the tarsi)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3675234" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3675234/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Figs 2, 3</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,760,1725,2068]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">
Head retracted in prothorax, only frons visible (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figs 2–7" captionStartId="2.[151,188,1643,1662]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,189,1627]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,189,1630]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 2–7.Amber inclusion of Platypelochares electricus sp. nov. 2 – amber piece with the studied specimen.3–7 – morphological details of P.electricus: 3 – ventral view; 4 – detail of the tubercle row on the pronotum (indicated by an arrow); 5 – detail of the ventral side of prosternum and right hypomeron, with the excavation (indicated by an arrow); 6 – lateral view; 7 – metacoxa and first four abdominal ventrites (arrow – lateral articulation of the tarsi)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3675234" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3675234/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). With a sharp carina bordering upper margin of eyes and clypeus, which is not visible. Antennae folded, not clearly visible.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,760,1725,2068]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">
Pronotum with a regular row of small tubercles in anterior part, extending laterally over the flattened lateral areas (
<figureCitation box="[218,282,2013,2036]" captionStart="Figs 2–7" captionStartId="2.[151,188,1643,1662]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,189,1627]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,189,1630]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 2–7.Amber inclusion of Platypelochares electricus sp. nov. 2 – amber piece with the studied specimen.3–7 – morphological details of P.electricus: 3 – ventral view; 4 – detail of the tubercle row on the pronotum (indicated by an arrow); 5 – detail of the ventral side of prosternum and right hypomeron, with the excavation (indicated by an arrow); 6 – lateral view; 7 – metacoxa and first four abdominal ventrites (arrow – lateral articulation of the tarsi)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3675234" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3675234/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). Hypomera with a fossa covered with a white undifferentiated substance (
<figureCitation box="[446,541,2045,2068]" captionStart="Figs 2–7" captionStartId="2.[151,188,1643,1662]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,189,1627]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,189,1630]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 2–7.Amber inclusion of Platypelochares electricus sp. nov. 2 – amber piece with the studied specimen.3–7 – morphological details of P.electricus: 3 – ventral view; 4 – detail of the tubercle row on the pronotum (indicated by an arrow); 5 – detail of the ventral side of prosternum and right hypomeron, with the excavation (indicated by an arrow); 6 – lateral view; 7 – metacoxa and first four abdominal ventrites (arrow – lateral articulation of the tarsi)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3675234" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3675234/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Figs 3, 5</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[828,1437,623,1798]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">
Elytral surface smooth and shiny, with a fine microreticulation, difficult to observe (
<figureCitation box="[1153,1217,655,678]" captionStart="Figs 2–7" captionStartId="2.[151,188,1643,1662]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,189,1627]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,189,1630]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 2–7.Amber inclusion of Platypelochares electricus sp. nov. 2 – amber piece with the studied specimen.3–7 – morphological details of P.electricus: 3 – ventral view; 4 – detail of the tubercle row on the pronotum (indicated by an arrow); 5 – detail of the ventral side of prosternum and right hypomeron, with the excavation (indicated by an arrow); 6 – lateral view; 7 – metacoxa and first four abdominal ventrites (arrow – lateral articulation of the tarsi)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3675234" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3675234/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). Elytral pubescence perfectly preserved, all pores with setae (
<figureCitation box="[1263,1329,687,710]" captionStart="Figs 2–7" captionStartId="2.[151,188,1643,1662]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,189,1627]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,189,1630]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 2–7.Amber inclusion of Platypelochares electricus sp. nov. 2 – amber piece with the studied specimen.3–7 – morphological details of P.electricus: 3 – ventral view; 4 – detail of the tubercle row on the pronotum (indicated by an arrow); 5 – detail of the ventral side of prosternum and right hypomeron, with the excavation (indicated by an arrow); 6 – lateral view; 7 – metacoxa and first four abdominal ventrites (arrow – lateral articulation of the tarsi)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3675234" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3675234/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). Margins explanate, visible from below (
<figureCitation box="[1153,1216,719,742]" captionStart="Figs 2–7" captionStartId="2.[151,188,1643,1662]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,189,1627]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,189,1630]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 2–7.Amber inclusion of Platypelochares electricus sp. nov. 2 – amber piece with the studied specimen.3–7 – morphological details of P.electricus: 3 – ventral view; 4 – detail of the tubercle row on the pronotum (indicated by an arrow); 5 – detail of the ventral side of prosternum and right hypomeron, with the excavation (indicated by an arrow); 6 – lateral view; 7 – metacoxa and first four abdominal ventrites (arrow – lateral articulation of the tarsi)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3675234" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3675234/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). Apex of elytra with a small apical semicircular excavation, apparently not protruding in middle. Epipleura with punctation coarser and denser than on rest of ventral surface (
<figureCitation box="[1281,1346,815,838]" captionStart="Figs 2–7" captionStartId="2.[151,188,1643,1662]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,189,1627]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,189,1630]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 2–7.Amber inclusion of Platypelochares electricus sp. nov. 2 – amber piece with the studied specimen.3–7 – morphological details of P.electricus: 3 – ventral view; 4 – detail of the tubercle row on the pronotum (indicated by an arrow); 5 – detail of the ventral side of prosternum and right hypomeron, with the excavation (indicated by an arrow); 6 – lateral view; 7 – metacoxa and first four abdominal ventrites (arrow – lateral articulation of the tarsi)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3675234" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3675234/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[828,1437,623,1798]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">
Ventral surface with double punctation: sparse large setiferous punctures, especially on metaventrite, and finer, equally sparse punctures (
<figureCitation box="[1112,1179,911,934]" captionStart="Figs 2–7" captionStartId="2.[151,188,1643,1662]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,189,1627]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,189,1630]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 2–7.Amber inclusion of Platypelochares electricus sp. nov. 2 – amber piece with the studied specimen.3–7 – morphological details of P.electricus: 3 – ventral view; 4 – detail of the tubercle row on the pronotum (indicated by an arrow); 5 – detail of the ventral side of prosternum and right hypomeron, with the excavation (indicated by an arrow); 6 – lateral view; 7 – metacoxa and first four abdominal ventrites (arrow – lateral articulation of the tarsi)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3675234" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3675234/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). Surface of abdominal ventrites with rough punctation (
<figureCitation box="[1180,1247,943,966]" captionStart="Figs 2–7" captionStartId="2.[151,188,1643,1662]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,189,1627]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,189,1630]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 2–7.Amber inclusion of Platypelochares electricus sp. nov. 2 – amber piece with the studied specimen.3–7 – morphological details of P.electricus: 3 – ventral view; 4 – detail of the tubercle row on the pronotum (indicated by an arrow); 5 – detail of the ventral side of prosternum and right hypomeron, with the excavation (indicated by an arrow); 6 – lateral view; 7 – metacoxa and first four abdominal ventrites (arrow – lateral articulation of the tarsi)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3675234" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3675234/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). Lateral margins of 2nd visible sternite glabrous and smooth, with a fine microreticulation, with excavations for reception of metatarsi (
<figureCitation box="[906,971,1039,1062]" captionStart="Figs 2–7" captionStartId="2.[151,188,1643,1662]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,189,1627]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,189,1630]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 2–7.Amber inclusion of Platypelochares electricus sp. nov. 2 – amber piece with the studied specimen.3–7 – morphological details of P.electricus: 3 – ventral view; 4 – detail of the tubercle row on the pronotum (indicated by an arrow); 5 – detail of the ventral side of prosternum and right hypomeron, with the excavation (indicated by an arrow); 6 – lateral view; 7 – metacoxa and first four abdominal ventrites (arrow – lateral articulation of the tarsi)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3675234" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3675234/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). Last abdominal ventrite with an apical tuff of longer setae (
<figureCitation box="[999,1064,1071,1094]" captionStart="Figs 2–7" captionStartId="2.[151,188,1643,1662]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,189,1627]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,189,1630]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 2–7.Amber inclusion of Platypelochares electricus sp. nov. 2 – amber piece with the studied specimen.3–7 – morphological details of P.electricus: 3 – ventral view; 4 – detail of the tubercle row on the pronotum (indicated by an arrow); 5 – detail of the ventral side of prosternum and right hypomeron, with the excavation (indicated by an arrow); 6 – lateral view; 7 – metacoxa and first four abdominal ventrites (arrow – lateral articulation of the tarsi)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3675234" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3675234/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[828,1437,623,1798]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">
Ventral surface of trochanters and femora with strong, sparse punctation. Ventral surface of tibiae with a denser, coarser punctation, with setae. Articulation of meso- and metatarsi with tibia lateral, not terminal. Underside of tarsi with long, stiff setae (
<figureCitation box="[1059,1156,1231,1254]" captionStart="Figs 2–7" captionStartId="2.[151,188,1643,1662]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,189,1627]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,189,1630]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 2–7.Amber inclusion of Platypelochares electricus sp. nov. 2 – amber piece with the studied specimen.3–7 – morphological details of P.electricus: 3 – ventral view; 4 – detail of the tubercle row on the pronotum (indicated by an arrow); 5 – detail of the ventral side of prosternum and right hypomeron, with the excavation (indicated by an arrow); 6 – lateral view; 7 – metacoxa and first four abdominal ventrites (arrow – lateral articulation of the tarsi)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3675234" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3675234/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Figs 5, 7</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="18" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[828,1437,623,1798]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[828,1052,1263,1286]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Comparative notes.</emphasis>
The presence of a row of tubercles on the pronotum places the new species within the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Champion" authorityYear="1923" class="Insecta" family="Limnichidae" genus="Platypelochares" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trifidus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">P. trifidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group sensu 
<bibRefCitation author="RIBERA I. &amp; HERNANDO C." box="[1049,1352,1327,1350]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" pagination="103 - 110" refId="ref2848" refString="RIBERA I. &amp; HERNANDO C. 1999: Taxonomic revision of Platypelochares Champion (Coleoptera: Limnichidae). Koleopterologische Rundschau 69: 103 - 110." type="journal article" year="1999">RIBERA &amp; HERNANDO (1999)</bibRefCitation>
. Within this group, it can be separated from other species by the length of the row of tubercles, being longer than in 
<taxonomicName authority="Champion, 1923" authorityName="Champion" authorityYear="1923" class="Insecta" family="Limnichidae" genus="Platypelochares" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latimargo">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">P. latimargo</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="CHAMPION G. C." box="[902,1079,1423,1446]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" pagination="269 - 277" refId="ref2447" refString="CHAMPION G. C. 1923: Some Indian Coleoptera (12). Entomologist's Monthly Magazine 59: 219 - 224, 269 - 277." type="journal article" year="1923">Champion, 1923</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Ribera &amp; Hernando, 1999" authorityName="Ribera &amp; Hernando" authorityYear="1999" class="Insecta" family="Limnichidae" genus="Platypelochares" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="periculosissimus">
<emphasis box="[1129,1333,1423,1447]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">P. periculosissimus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="RIBERA I. &amp; HERNANDO C." pageId="1" pageNumber="18" pagination="103 - 110" refId="ref2848" refString="RIBERA I. &amp; HERNANDO C. 1999: Taxonomic revision of Platypelochares Champion (Coleoptera: Limnichidae). Koleopterologische Rundschau 69: 103 - 110." type="journal article" year="1999">Ribera &amp; Hernando, 1999</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but of similar extension to 
<emphasis box="[1309,1436,1455,1479]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">P. chinensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="YOSHITOMI H." box="[828,1008,1487,1510]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" pagination="385 - 389" refId="ref3171" refString="YOSHITOMI H. 2011: A new species of the genus Platypelochares (Coleoptera, Limnichidae, Limnichinae) from China. Japanese Journal of Systematic Entomology 17: 385 - 389." type="journal article" year="2011">Yoshitomi, 2011</bibRefCitation>
. The body outline in dorsal view is also more similar to 
<emphasis box="[1005,1132,1519,1543]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">P. chinensis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="YOSHITOMI H." box="[1150,1326,1519,1542]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" pagination="385 - 389" refId="ref3171" refString="YOSHITOMI H. 2011: A new species of the genus Platypelochares (Coleoptera, Limnichidae, Limnichinae) from China. Japanese Journal of Systematic Entomology 17: 385 - 389." type="journal article" year="2011">YOSHITOMI 2011</bibRefCitation>
), with the elytra slightly acuminate, not almost perfectly circular as in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Champion" authorityYear="1923" box="[828,955,1583,1607]" class="Insecta" family="Limnichidae" genus="Platypelochares" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latimargo">
<emphasis box="[828,955,1583,1607]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">P. latimargo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<emphasis box="[987,1187,1583,1607]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">P. periculossisimus</emphasis>
. The elytral reticulation of 
<taxonomicName authority="Hernando &amp; Szawaryn &amp; Ribera, 2018" authorityName="Hernando &amp; Szawaryn &amp; Ribera" authorityYear="2018" box="[855,984,1615,1639]" class="Insecta" family="Limnichidae" genus="Platypelochares" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="electricus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[855,984,1615,1639]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">P. electricus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[989,1071,1615,1638]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is, however, less marked than in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">P. chinensis</emphasis>
, and the elytral pubescence is more sparse. The ventral punctation of 
<taxonomicName authority="Hernando &amp; Szawaryn &amp; Ribera, 2018" authorityName="Hernando &amp; Szawaryn &amp; Ribera" authorityYear="2018" box="[1054,1184,1679,1703]" class="Insecta" family="Limnichidae" genus="Platypelochares" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="electricus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1054,1184,1679,1703]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">P. electricus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1189,1271,1679,1702]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is also stronger and less dense than in all other species of the group.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="18" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[828,1437,623,1798]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[828,956,1743,1766]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Etymology.</emphasis>
From the Latin 
<emphasis box="[1124,1217,1743,1766]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">electrum</emphasis>
(= amber), adjective in nominative singular.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
